are going to combine into a very compelling challenge.

463
00:25:10,045 --> 00:25:12,187
So the act of playing Doom at this low level

464
00:25:12,267 --> 00:25:15,009
can be committed to procedural memory at some point, what

465
00:25:15,029 --> 00:25:16,030
we call muscle memory.

466
00:25:16,711 --> 00:25:18,973
At some point, I can actually play Doom in my sleep.

467
00:25:20,131 --> 00:25:25,595
It's not quite an innate behavior, but it's the closest we can get to actually having something imprinted in our brain.

468
00:25:27,096 --> 00:25:32,119
So everything about Doom kind of feeds into an established narrative of why we like action games so much.

469
00:25:32,259 --> 00:25:37,823
We are inherently motivated to achieve competence over an environment or an object.

470
00:25:38,223 --> 00:25:39,324
I still can't do this.

471
00:25:40,157 --> 00:25:43,200
And games are this really feedback-rich environment

472
00:25:43,300 --> 00:25:46,203
that test our survival skills and keep us optimally challenged

473
00:25:46,283 --> 00:25:48,966
as we're achieving mastery over all of the dangers

474
00:25:49,026 --> 00:25:51,328
which are literally like threatening our very existence.

475
00:25:52,089 --> 00:25:54,612
Now the question here is that the way we talk about dooms,

476
00:25:54,672 --> 00:25:56,234
we're talking about survival skills.

477
00:25:56,714 --> 00:25:58,336
Does that actually have to do anything with choice?

478
00:25:59,240 --> 00:26:04,924
Like I said earlier that decisions are bound to be meaningful when they fulfill some sort of base psychological need like competence,

479
00:26:04,984 --> 00:26:10,187
but how does this actually apply to skill checks, survival skills, because this is supposed to be instinctual, right?

480
00:26:10,267 --> 00:26:12,728
It's supposed to be imprinted in our muscle memory.

481
00:26:13,489 --> 00:26:15,650
So where at the lowest level is the choice here?

482
00:26:16,591 --> 00:26:21,173
Maybe my entire thesis just falls apart and I shouldn't have done this talk, but I mean that's part of the narrative.

483
00:26:21,273 --> 00:26:26,296
Doom is a really good action game. Action games are fun and compelling and meaningful because, well, tense,

484
00:26:26,777 --> 00:26:28,478
and oh my god, look at all the skill checks.

485
00:26:29,045 --> 00:26:30,825
But in fact, if you're looking at my design razor,

486
00:26:30,925 --> 00:26:34,326
I have explicitly put skill check as a component in there.

487
00:26:34,346 --> 00:26:36,967
So I can actually test for that, like the Twitch skills, which

488
00:26:37,007 --> 00:26:37,967
are going to come out of something.

489
00:26:38,687 --> 00:26:40,208
Now, one thing we have to remember here,

490
00:26:40,548 --> 00:26:43,169
where it doesn't fall apart, is that a skill check is not

491
00:26:43,209 --> 00:26:44,429
something a player actually does.

492
00:26:44,629 --> 00:26:46,270
It's something that a player reacts to.

493
00:26:46,850 --> 00:26:50,271
And how we react to the skill check is by making decisions.

494
00:26:51,571 --> 00:26:52,651
According to Glu2 Games.

495
00:26:53,584 --> 00:26:57,347
Blue2Games, a game has to have three properties to fulfill these competent needs.

496
00:26:57,507 --> 00:27:01,990
It has to have clarity about the goal at hand, challenge that is not overwhelming,

497
00:27:02,551 --> 00:27:05,753
and clear feedback on our actions that make us feel like we learned something.

498
00:27:05,873 --> 00:27:07,855
And it's exactly this last part right here.

499
00:27:09,022 --> 00:27:13,665
That is so important, because it actually does explain how games are meaningful at the moment-to-moment level.

500
00:27:14,125 --> 00:27:18,548
Because if we do react to skill checks by making decisions and adjusting our aim and so on,

501
00:27:18,929 --> 00:27:20,450
we need to be fully in control.

502
00:27:20,750 --> 00:27:24,873
And that requires very good science and feedback as well as very good controls in the first place.

503
00:27:26,437 --> 00:27:30,763
So what I really mean when I ask, what is the skill check or the meaningful choice, is probably this.

504
00:27:32,085 --> 00:27:39,815
How good are the 3Cs and the science and feedback that are implicated whenever the game expects me to react to a skill check by making a split-second decision?

505
00:27:42,755 --> 00:27:46,037
Because I can only make split-second decisions really well if the three C's,

506
00:27:46,277 --> 00:27:48,058
camera, character, control, are awesome.

507
00:27:48,499 --> 00:27:51,201
And when the science and feedback I'm getting to everything that I'm doing

508
00:27:51,261 --> 00:27:52,642
is very clear and unambiguous.

509
00:27:52,942 --> 00:27:54,663
Because then I can get into this flow state

510
00:27:54,723 --> 00:27:57,465
where the controls just melt away and I'm one with the game.

511
00:27:57,945 --> 00:28:01,068
And that's where my competence needs are actually fulfilled,

512
00:28:01,128 --> 00:28:04,210
because the amount of immediate feedback from the game,

513
00:28:04,930 --> 00:28:06,732
like to each of my low-level actions,

514
00:28:06,832 --> 00:28:10,234
actually allows me to master all of the skill checks that the game is throwing at me.

515
00:28:12,640 --> 00:28:16,063
So science and feedback, at least in the skill check scenario,

516
00:28:16,083 --> 00:28:19,486
are actually the lowest level in which a game creates systemic agency,

517
00:28:19,646 --> 00:28:20,907
and agency in general.

518
00:28:21,548 --> 00:28:24,651
And that might be a little bit weird because the way we usually talk about agency

519
00:28:25,031 --> 00:28:27,573
is in terms of big decisions and big choices.

520
00:28:27,973 --> 00:28:32,177
In fact, we often abuse it now to just say something like player freedom, which is wrong.

521
00:28:33,058 --> 00:28:35,100
Agency just means, at the simplest level,

522
00:28:35,160 --> 00:28:37,822
that it is the satisfying power to take meaningful action

523
00:28:37,862 --> 00:28:40,104
and see the results of our decisions and choices.

524
00:28:40,799 --> 00:28:45,382
And that's exactly a big part of the reason why we feel so much in control of the combat encounter

525
00:28:45,582 --> 00:28:47,883
when we get into this slow state in a game like this,

526
00:28:47,963 --> 00:28:53,407
because of the low-level systemic agency that's afforded via the science and feedback in the three Cs.

527
00:28:56,088 --> 00:28:59,210
And that then in return creates satisfaction of our competence needs, right?

528
00:28:59,230 --> 00:29:01,911
That's what we're feeling really good about having mastered this environment.

529
00:29:02,790 --> 00:29:06,571
So you might actually say that Doom at the lowest level is a series of interesting decisions.

530
00:29:06,991 --> 00:29:10,993
Although you might really have to say it's a series of low-level control-related decisions.

531
00:29:12,033 --> 00:29:15,515
But everything I do in this game is discernible and integrated, and the decisions that I make,

532
00:29:15,875 --> 00:29:19,276
such as how to move around, where to move, when to shoot, actually matter.

533
00:29:20,937 --> 00:29:22,077
So, that's part of this.

534
00:29:22,537 --> 00:29:25,799
Mastering skill checks via good pre-season, via good science and feedback.

535
00:29:26,059 --> 00:29:29,460
And they do need to be good, because if they're not good, we can't control the game,

536
00:29:29,500 --> 00:29:31,461
and then the competence needs aren't actually fulfilled.

537
00:29:31,993 --> 00:29:33,173
But this creates agency.

538
00:29:34,494 --> 00:29:38,695
And this low-level agency that I'm talking about is certainly part of systemic agency

539
00:29:38,735 --> 00:29:42,176
and making sure that, you know, the game plays and feels good.

540
00:29:42,736 --> 00:29:44,357
Now, of course, the question is, is that all?

541
00:29:44,477 --> 00:29:49,579
Because if the fulfillment of all the competence needs is the only good thing that an action game needs,

542
00:29:50,179 --> 00:29:52,499
there's a lot of games out there that should be awesome, right?

543
00:29:53,300 --> 00:29:55,821
Glut2Games actually has a section in which it analyzes Doom,

544
00:29:55,861 --> 00:29:57,541
specifically through the lens of competence.

545
00:29:57,561 --> 00:29:59,182
It's kind of one of their poster childs.

546
00:29:59,742 --> 00:30:00,682
And it makes this argument.

547
00:30:02,030 --> 00:30:02,451
It says that,

548
00:30:03,031 --> 00:30:04,932
it is the gradual progression of challenges

549
00:30:05,012 --> 00:30:06,473
as the player marches into hell

550
00:30:06,793 --> 00:30:09,095
that provides the strongest motivational pull of doom

551
00:30:09,295 --> 00:30:11,496
in virtually all successful FPS games.

552
00:30:12,117 --> 00:30:13,097
That progression is key.

553
00:30:13,457 --> 00:30:15,099
With each hellish opponent you fell,

554
00:30:15,119 --> 00:30:18,000
there's a small victory won on your road to the larger goal.

555
00:30:18,401 --> 00:30:19,741
From a competence standpoint,

556
00:30:20,002 --> 00:30:21,743
these small moment-to-moment victories

557
00:30:21,803 --> 00:30:23,043
are more like a trail of chocolates,

558
00:30:23,384 --> 00:30:25,565
each providing a small bite of satisfaction

559
00:30:25,625 --> 00:30:27,306
as the player succeeds and progresses

560
00:30:27,346 --> 00:30:28,307
towards a larger victory.

561
00:30:29,147 --> 00:30:29,988
That's quite poetic.

562
00:30:31,540 --> 00:30:32,781
I don't want to put words in their mouth.

563
00:30:32,821 --> 00:30:34,662
To me, this reads a little bit like what they're saying

564
00:30:34,722 --> 00:30:39,484
is that you need to be able to point a gun at somebody,

565
00:30:39,624 --> 00:30:41,505
and you need to be able to overcome a progression

566
00:30:41,525 --> 00:30:43,306
of challenges, of skill checks.

567
00:30:44,227 --> 00:30:46,568
And if you do that, you're going to have a really successful

568
00:30:46,788 --> 00:30:47,668
first-person shooter game.

569
00:30:48,329 --> 00:30:48,949
Don't get me wrong.

570
00:30:48,969 --> 00:30:50,610
I actually do agree with this in one way.

571
00:30:50,950 --> 00:30:53,211
I do believe that Doom's rational level design,

572
00:30:53,371 --> 00:30:55,672
like the game system story, of which I didn't have a picture

573
00:30:55,692 --> 00:30:57,973
except for 1313, I believe this is important.

574
00:30:58,253 --> 00:30:58,554
Like, um.

575
00:31:01,937 --> 00:31:07,204
overcoming the challenges thrown at me in Doom and how finely that's tuned is a big part of why that game is good,

576
00:31:07,244 --> 00:31:12,651
but having played as much Doom as I have in my lifetime and just playing the same level over and over again,

577
00:31:12,671 --> 00:31:15,896
I think if we just have this outlook, we seriously missed a mark.

578
00:31:16,561 --> 00:31:21,402
Because we're trying to identify competence needs as the main reason as to why Doom's gameplay was so successful.

579
00:31:21,482 --> 00:31:26,323
And how many modern games do you know that have good aiming, good movement, good science and feedback,

580
00:31:26,723 --> 00:31:29,464
and they probably have an enemy progression as well, but things get harder,

581
00:31:29,484 --> 00:31:33,064
and they're still not really fun to play because there's some sort of spark missing?

582
00:31:33,604 --> 00:31:37,445
I mean, hell, I only have to stay within the same franchise and go one game down

583
00:31:37,505 --> 00:31:41,506
to know that a competent execution of a progression of challenges is just not enough.

584
00:31:43,875 --> 00:31:46,937
So there's a danger to thinking about action games in terms of competence only.

585
00:31:47,938 --> 00:31:50,399
And that's a trap that many games unfortunately fall into.

586
00:31:50,419 --> 00:31:53,161
I would have loved to play an extra clip here.

587
00:31:53,701 --> 00:31:57,964
But this is why playing Doom 1 and 2, analyzing Doom 1 and 2, is really a big deal to me.

588
00:31:58,004 --> 00:31:58,724
That's why I'm doing it.

589
00:31:58,784 --> 00:32:03,287
Because to me, it's the reminder that Doom doesn't just frame its core component, its

590
00:32:03,307 --> 00:32:05,168
systemic agency, in terms of competence.

591
00:32:07,489 --> 00:32:09,991
There's something else to Doom, something else that needs to be there.

592
00:32:11,022 --> 00:32:14,745
to really make good combat in these kind of shooters,

593
00:32:15,185 --> 00:32:17,867
something that satisfies another psychological need,

594
00:32:17,907 --> 00:32:18,647
and that's autonomy.

595
00:32:19,288 --> 00:32:21,889
And pretty much what this comes down to is that Doom works

596
00:32:21,949 --> 00:32:25,011
because it has orthogonal unit differentiation.

597
00:32:25,672 --> 00:32:29,554
Now, I love the term orthogonal unit differentiation

598
00:32:29,594 --> 00:32:31,636
because in pretentiousness and awkwardness,

599
00:32:31,736 --> 00:32:34,057
it's only second to ludonarrative dissonance.

600
00:32:35,878 --> 00:32:37,700
So I'll spare myself some trouble here.

601
00:32:40,905 --> 00:32:45,527
I'll just call it OUD, or simply differentiation, but we should talk about it.

602
00:32:45,547 --> 00:32:51,130
It's something that Harvey Smith introduced at GDC in 2003, so this was like 11 years ago.

603
00:32:51,930 --> 00:32:57,693
OUD gives us a way to talk about how game systems are meaningfully differentiated in their abilities and behaviors,

604
00:32:58,293 --> 00:33:01,515
and how that distinction leads to some interesting and complex gameplay.

605
00:33:01,975 --> 00:33:05,756
It leads to what I called in 2012 an expressive possibility space.

606
00:33:06,272 --> 00:33:07,954
But once again, this was a little bit misleading.

607
00:33:07,994 --> 00:33:09,276
So I'm going to take it from the top

608
00:33:09,716 --> 00:33:11,699
and actually start by establishing a better

609
00:33:11,739 --> 00:33:15,163
presentation or representation of Doom's possibilities

610
00:33:15,204 --> 00:33:15,985
based in the first place.

611
00:33:18,052 --> 00:33:20,973
And here's something that you figure out after playing Doom for a long time.

612
00:33:21,513 --> 00:33:25,655
The enemies and the weapon in this game are actually really finely tuned to interact on

613
00:33:25,695 --> 00:33:26,556
multiple axes.

614
00:33:26,876 --> 00:33:30,878
What first looks like this visceral, barely controllable, maybe even simplistic fight

615
00:33:30,898 --> 00:33:36,140
for survival is actually this really complex interplay of many gameplay elements that allow

616
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:38,061
forever new tactics and strategies.

617
00:33:38,581 --> 00:33:39,902
And this all happens via OUD.

618
00:33:40,535 --> 00:33:42,496
Because if you're looking at the enemy classes in Doom,

619
00:33:42,636 --> 00:33:44,417
I can map every single enemy type

620
00:33:44,497 --> 00:33:48,978
across some orthogonally differentiated categories.

621
00:33:49,699 --> 00:33:52,139
There's an axis where I can map all of the hitscan

622
00:33:52,159 --> 00:33:53,260
versus projectile guys.

623
00:33:53,660 --> 00:33:56,061
Those are the two classes of enemies that exist in Doom.

624
00:33:57,461 --> 00:33:59,942
And then I can also do this by the amount of damage they do.

625
00:34:00,522 --> 00:34:01,983
And then there's a second axis, which

626
00:34:02,023 --> 00:34:04,584
are charging enemies versus enemies which stay back,

627
00:34:04,764 --> 00:34:06,664
which is just a function of their overall speed,

628
00:34:06,704 --> 00:34:09,165
but also the behavior that they're subject to.

629
00:34:09,833 --> 00:34:13,354
Then if I put all of this together, I can create a chart that looks like this.

630
00:34:13,594 --> 00:34:16,875
And this is actually a pretty accurate representation of Doom's possibility space,

631
00:34:16,915 --> 00:34:20,296
at least as it pertains to these specific enemies and what's important to me.

632
00:34:20,976 --> 00:34:25,236
And as you notice, the enemy distribution actually already covers a large part of the entire spectrum.

633
00:34:25,777 --> 00:34:28,957
I left out some enemies there, so I'm sure I could pretty much fill it in all the way.

634
00:34:29,497 --> 00:34:33,938
But what this does is allow the player to have a very specific opinion on each enemy type,

635
00:34:33,978 --> 00:34:35,398
because they know what they stand for.

636
00:34:35,779 --> 00:34:38,279
And that allows them to prioritize enemies in each encounter.

637
00:34:39,540 --> 00:34:44,503
So if I'm looking at this example, which enemy would you want to take out first with your shotgun?

638
00:34:45,424 --> 00:34:51,188
I'm assuming it's that black shotgunner dude back there because he has a hitscan weapon and he can deal immediate damage.

639
00:34:51,469 --> 00:34:56,012
And I know about this. Whereas all those fireballs that are thrown at me, I can dodge those.

640
00:34:56,352 --> 00:34:59,294
Those guys are called imps, by the way, in case you didn't play Doom.

641
00:35:00,956 --> 00:35:07,941
So the reason why Doom works so well is that each enemy represents a distinct, consistent, and discernible behavior that can be learned.

642
00:35:08,686 --> 00:35:11,688
And because there are only a few traits to all of these enemies,

643
00:35:12,388 --> 00:35:14,029
which just fall across two axes,

644
00:35:14,329 --> 00:35:15,770
I can actually learn this rather quickly.

645
00:35:16,290 --> 00:35:19,092
So this is information that players are going to internalize,

646
00:35:19,112 --> 00:35:20,192
and that's really important to them.

647
00:35:20,232 --> 00:35:22,673
So I want to look at how the player actually processes

648
00:35:22,733 --> 00:35:24,214
and stores this kind of information.

649
00:35:24,835 --> 00:35:27,976
And they do this via a psychological construct called a schema,

650
00:35:28,637 --> 00:35:31,278
which is an organized pattern of thought or behavior

651
00:35:31,558 --> 00:35:33,579
that organizes categories of information

652
00:35:34,460 --> 00:35:35,700
and the relationship among them.

653
00:35:36,524 --> 00:35:39,445
And then information which is thrown at me is either assimilated,

654
00:35:39,905 --> 00:35:42,907
it's pretty much integrated into the schema, into an existing one,

655
00:35:43,327 --> 00:35:46,249
or it can be accommodated, which means that it doesn't fit.

656
00:35:46,289 --> 00:35:48,911
I actually have to create a new schema for this information

657
00:35:48,951 --> 00:35:53,513
because I realized that a striped horse is actually a zebra and not a striped horse.

658
00:35:55,475 --> 00:35:58,256
We can actually be a little bit finer with what exactly a schema is,

659
00:35:58,416 --> 00:36:00,437
and we can do this by what information they store.

660
00:36:00,918 --> 00:36:03,019
We call schemas a frame.

661
00:36:03,961 --> 00:36:06,562
when they contain properties and behaviors of something,

662
00:36:06,622 --> 00:36:08,523
and we call them a script when they

663
00:36:08,843 --> 00:36:11,924
hold some sort of processes how we approach a situation

664
00:36:12,505 --> 00:36:13,765
or how we deal with an object.

665
00:36:13,825 --> 00:36:16,766
So in Doom's case, the attributes of the enemy

666
00:36:16,786 --> 00:36:20,368
would be its frame, while the player tactics of how

667
00:36:20,388 --> 00:36:22,429
to actually approach this enemy would be its script.

668
00:36:23,669 --> 00:36:25,810
And players can easily create frames and scripts

669
00:36:25,870 --> 00:36:27,091
for each enemy type in Doom.

670
00:36:27,491 --> 00:36:29,272
They know exactly what the enemy represents,

671
00:36:29,352 --> 00:36:30,312
how best to deal with them.

672
00:36:31,247 --> 00:36:34,167
And everything is very clear-cut because it's all differentiated.

673
00:36:35,288 --> 00:36:36,048
So far, so good.

674
00:36:36,408 --> 00:36:40,689
All of the individual units have clear and concise properties and behaviors,

675
00:36:40,729 --> 00:36:44,590
which creates some very clearly discernible patterns to each one of these guys.

676
00:36:44,991 --> 00:36:48,772
And just each pattern encountered on its own is going to be a no-brainer.

677
00:36:49,452 --> 00:36:52,113
What's interesting is what happens once I put them into conflict,

678
00:36:52,173 --> 00:36:54,353
because then, quite literally, all hell breaks loose.

679
00:36:54,753 --> 00:36:56,334
Looking back at this picture right here,

680
00:36:57,474 --> 00:36:59,255
do we really want to take out the shotgunner first?

681
00:36:59,875 --> 00:37:03,159
Is that a script that I can reliably follow for all of Doom?

682
00:37:03,399 --> 00:37:04,960
Deal with the hitscan guys first.

683
00:37:05,501 --> 00:37:08,403
Because that black dude in the back certainly can shoot us immediately

684
00:37:08,484 --> 00:37:11,146
while I dodge all the fireballs by those imps,

685
00:37:11,226 --> 00:37:14,729
except that that imp over there has actually gotten pretty close to me, right?

686
00:37:14,809 --> 00:37:16,811
I might not be able to strafe out of the way anymore.

687
00:37:17,372 --> 00:37:18,993
So this is actually a judgment call.

688
00:37:19,033 --> 00:37:22,356
I don't actually know exactly how I'm going to prioritize the situation.

689
00:37:23,086 --> 00:37:26,009
And I call this, funnily enough, prioritization choice,

690
00:37:26,349 --> 00:37:29,892
because I get to have an opinion on how to approach this encounter

691
00:37:30,293 --> 00:37:31,694
and how I prioritize it.

692
00:37:34,176 --> 00:37:38,020
Now, prioritization choice is created from the complex interplay of systems

693
00:37:38,260 --> 00:37:39,901
that are easily understood individually,

694
00:37:40,302 --> 00:37:43,344
but that combine into situations that don't have a consistent

695
00:37:43,464 --> 00:37:44,986
or obviously superior tactic.

